The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                Sheikh Israfil, alias Sumon, who had allegedly hacked to death Oxytown homemaker Mausumi Ghosh and her help Parul, was arrested on Tuesday night. Sources said he had been picked up from a Thakurpukur hideout. Police came to know about Israfil from Somenath Tanti, a key accused whom Mausumis husband Avik Ghosh had allegedly hired to get her killed. The police launched a search for Israfil after interrogating Avik and Tanti on Tuesday evening.    A 54-year-old woman died after being run over by a state bus on Bidhan Sarani in central Calcutta on Tuesday morning. Police said Basanti Dutta, a resident of adjacent College Row, was returning home when she was hit by the bus. She was taken to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital, she was declared dead on arrival. The bus was seized but the driver fled.     The post-mortem on Mita Dey, the wife of a Reserve Bank of India official who was found dead at her Dover Lane apartment on Monday morning, has not revealed any evidence of foul play. Dulal Ghosh, the officer-in-charge of Gariahat police station, said there was no hint of the 49-year-old woman having been murdered. Police sources said the woman might have suffered a cardiac arrest after an overdose of medicines. No complaint has been lodged though Mitas father had on Monday suspected foul play in his daughters death.    A couple in their 40s committed suicide by hanging themselves at their Behala home on Tuesday afternoon. Subal Sarkar, a carpenter, and wife Shikha had been suffering from depression since the death of their 15-year-old daughter five months ago.     Nemai Mandal, accused of strangulating two-and-a-half-year-old Gopal Dalui in Domjur on Sunday, was produced in Howrahs chief judicial magistrate court on Tuesday and remanded in judicial custody for 14 days. He was booked for murder and abduction.    The Jadavpur University unit of All Bengal University Teachers Association, an anti-CPM organisation, submitted a memorandum to vice-chancellor P.N. Ghosh, demanding immediate steps to restore normal academic activities. The teachers also demanded that the authorities withdraw the FIR against 35 students who had allegedly created trouble when chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee visited the campus on November 9.    A 36-year-old mason died when the wall of a dilapidated house in Ramnagar in Uluberia collapsed on him on Tuesday afternoon. Police said the mishap occurred when Bikas Das was erecting a wall of an adjoining house. Residents took Das to Uluberia Sub-divisional Hospital, where he was declared dead on arrival.    A scuffle broke out at the North 24-Parganas district court on Tuesday after the Law Clerk Association called a ceasework to mourn the death of one of its members, Ramendranath Banerjee. As the association tried to prevent lawyers and litigants from entering the court, a scuffle broke out between the lawyers and the clerks. Hundreds of litigants, some of whom had come from other states, had to go back without being able to get their work done.     Commodore Brian A. Thomas on Tuesday took over as naval officer-in-charge, West Bengal, and commanding officer of INS Netaji Subhash. He has served as naval   fficer-in-charge in Andhra Pradesh, commissioning executive officer in INS Nireekshak and Matanga. He was also commanding officer of INS Saryu.    A hunger strike by the Indian Association of Physiotherapists outside Sashthya Bhavan in Salt Lake was called off on Tuesday.            
